sh  <i>plegstede</i>,  <i>plægstede</i>). The surname may be for someone who lived near a place for physical or theatrical play, or for someone from a place so named, such as Chapel Plaster in Box (Wilts), which is recorded as  <i>Pleystede</i> in 1268.  Compare  Plastow  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Playsted","meanings":["English:  see  Plested  ."]},{"name":"Plastow","meanings":["English: locative name from Middle English  <i>plei(e)</i> ‘play, game, performance’ +  <i>stou(e)</i> ‘place, location’ (Old English  <i>plegstōw</i>, * <i>plægstōw</i>). The surname may be for someone who lived near a place for physical or theatrical play, or for someone from any of numerous places so named, such as Plaistow (Essex, Surrey, Gloucs, Devon, Sussex), Playstow (Herts), Pleystowe (Surrey), or Plastow (Hants).  Compare  Plested  ."]},{"name":"Plaisted","meanings":["English (mainly Kent): topographic name from Middle English <i>plei(e)</i> ‘play, game, performance’ + <i>stede</i> ‘place, location’ (Old English <i>plegstede</i>, <i>plægstede</i>). The surname may be for someone who lived near a place for physical or theatrical play, or from a place so named, such as Chapel Plaster in Wiltshire. Compare   Plaster   2."]},{"name":"Plaster","meanings":["English and North German: metonymic occupational name for a plasterer, from Middle English, Middle Low German <i>plaster</i> (from Latin <i>emplastrum</i> ‘(wound) plaster’ (originally a paste), from Greek <i>emplastron</i>, a derivative of <i>emplassein</i> ‘to shape or form’; the term was carried over into building terminology to mean ‘bonding agent’).","English: variant from a common pronunciation of <b>Plastow</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Plaistow (in East London, Derbyshire, Sussex, and elsewhere), from Old English <i>plegestōw</i> ‘place where people gather for sport or play’. This can also be a variant of   Plaisted   (through interchangeable use of the Old English elements <i>stōw</i> and <i>stede</i>, both meaning ‘place’, in earlier times).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from German <i>Pflaster</i> ‘(street) pavement’."]},{"name":"Playle","meanings":["English (Essex): apparently a habitational name from an unidentified place called in Old English <i>plega</i> ‘play, sport’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Plaster   2."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joyouse Prested was born in 1215, in Epping, Essex, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Prested. She married Gilbert de Grenville in 1238, in Colne Engaine, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died on 28 March 1274, in Byfield, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1215–28 March 1274":"1215–28. märts 1274","1215–1274":"1215–1274","1215–1243":"1215–1243","1236–1305":"1236–1305","–Male":"Surnud","1305":"1305","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1243":"1243","2 November 1243":"2. november 1243","1274":"1274","28 March 1274":"28. märts 1274","Byfield, Northamptonshire, England":"Byfield, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Epping, Essex, England":"Epping, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hallaton, Leicestershire, England":"Hallaton, Leicestershire, England","Colne Engaine, Essex, England":"Colne Engaine, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hallaton, Uppingham, Leicestershire, England":"Hallaton, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"1215–28 March 1274":"1215–28. maaliskuuta 1274","1215–1274":"1215–1274","1215–1243":"1215–1243","1236–1305":"1236–1305","–Male":"Kuollut","1305":"1305","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1243":"1243","2 November 1243":"2. marraskuuta 1243","1274":"1274","28 March 1274":"28. maaliskuuta 1274","Byfield, Northamptonshire, England":"Byfield, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Epping, Essex, England":"Epping, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hallaton, Leicestershire, England":"Hallaton, Leicestershire, England","Colne Engaine, Essex, England":"Colne Engaine, Essex, Englanti, Yh